<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-631-242  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 631 242.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  May 17 1990 n1214 p58(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Better diction for British business. (Collins On-Line Dictionary)(Software Review) (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gannon, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Multinational corporations are faced with the challenge ofcommunicating in more than one language, and a good dictionary isessential for meeting this challenge.andP;  When using a wordprocessor, an electronic dictionary enhances the process and ismuch easier to browse than a hardcopy version.andP;  Collins' secondversion of its On-Line Electronic Dictionary is a good choice.andO;Its ability to work in conjunction with a word processing package,occupying the bottom half of a screen and pasting the selectedtranslation into the document, is its best feature.andP;  One drawbackis that whatever version of the dictionary is selected, it onlyprovides one-way translation.andP;  That is, Spanish-to-English is onedictionary, while English-to-Spanish is a separate version.andP;  Thesystem could be more user-friendly, and the accuracy is somewhatless than that of hardcopy dictionaries, but it is still a goodvalue at 75 pounds sterling.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Collins On-Line Electronic Dictionary (Computer program).andO;Topic:     EvaluationOn-LineDictionaries.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>